  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Your goal in the friendly match was a real triumph — how has that moment stayed with you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "It was amazing! I still feel happy when I think about it. My friends said it was a great shot. I just wanted to help my team win. We celebrated a lot after that. Do you watch football matches?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Scored for the team and celebrated it — that’s the best kind of win. Friends’ praise is a nice bonus, but the joy of contributing stays with you. I know a good goal when I see one. What’s next — a new match or another photo you’re working on?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Actually, I’m preparing for a bank PO exam these days, so I don’t get to play as much. But when I do, I try to take good photos of the matches. Photography is my other passion — you know, capturing those winning moments! Do you like watching football?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Banking prep and football moments — a great balance of focus and passion. It’s lovely that you capture matches when you can. What kinds of shots do you like best — goals, teamwork, or something else?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I like action shots the most — when a player is about to score or making a great pass. Sometimes I also take close-ups of players' faces to show their emotions. It's amazing how a single moment can tell a whole story. But honestly, I still have a lot to learn. Any tips for better sports photography?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Action shots and close-ups — you already see the story in a moment. That’s a great eye. Try freezing motion with a fast shutter speed when someone’s about to score. What’s one shot you wish you could take again?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "There was this one time during a local match — I was shooting from the sidelines — and the sun was going down. A player took a long shot from the halfway line, and the ball was in mid-air. I clicked, but the photo came out a bit blurred. I really want to get that exact moment sharp and clear. Maybe next time! By the way, do you like football, or are you more into other sports?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "That long shot under the sunset — you’re painting a picture with words already. Blurred once doesn’t mean you’ll miss it forever. What’s your go-to camera setting for golden-hour action?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I try using a higher shutter speed during golden hour, but sometimes the light is just tricky. I also keep my ISO a bit low to avoid noise, but maybe I should experiment more. Oh, and I use my phone a lot too — it’s not as good as a DSLR, but it’s always with me. Speaking of, I should probably get back to my study schedule. Gotta prepare for the next exam mock!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "You’re thinking about it just right — shutter speed and ISO are key in golden moments. Phones are handy, but a DSLR adds depth when you're ready. Take your time with studies — exams and football can wait, but the sunset shots? They're worth the chase. What’s your next mock exam about?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "My next mock is about quantitative aptitude — all numbers and calculations! It’s tough, but I try to take breaks and think about football or photography. Keeps my mind fresh. Maybe after the exam, I’ll go for a match and take some better photos. I need practice!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Quantitative aptitude can be a mental game — good strategy to reset with sports or photos. A fresh mind clicks faster. What’s one calculation trick you’ve found really helps?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I use the rule of 72 for quick interest calculations — it helps me estimate how long money takes to double. Also, breaking big problems into smaller steps makes them easier. But I still get stuck sometimes. You must have some tricks too! Anyway, I better go — my study time is running out. Talk to you soon!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Rule of 72 — smart move for quick estimates. Breaking big into small? That’s how champions and photographers think. What’s the biggest math hurdle you’ve conquered so far?"
    }
  ],
